article.description:
Michael Olowokandi scored a career-high 30 points, and Quentin Richardson had a huge basket down the stretch
as the Los Angeles Clippers beat the Chicago Bulls 94-90 Friday night.
article.headline: Olowokandi overshadows Brand's return to Chicago
article.linkText: Clippers' Brand wins first game back in Chicago
article.story:
CHICAGO -- Michael Olowokandi scored a career-high 30 points, and Quentin Richardson had a huge basket down the stretch as the Los Angeles Clippers beat the Chicago Bulls 94-90 Friday night. Olowokandi also had 16 rebounds for the Clippers, while Richardson finished with 16 points. Elton Brand, playing his first-regular season game in Chicago since being traded last summer, added 15 points and 10 boards. Jalen Rose and Trenton Hassell led the Bulls with 21 points apiece, and rookie Eddy Curry added 13 points and eight rebounds. The game was close all night, but the Clippers gained a slight edge in the fourth quarter. Curry's layup pulled the Bulls to 83-82 with 3:03 left, and Chicago had a chance to take the lead. But Rose's pass to Curry sailed out of bounds with 1:42 to play. Olowokandi and Richardson each made free throws, and Rose was called for an offensive foul. Then Richardson sliced through heavy traffic and lofted up a layup that swished through the basket, giving the Clippers an 87-82 lead with 1:07 remaining. The Bulls managed to closed to 92-90 on Rose's 3-pointer with 12.8 seconds to play, but they couldn't get any closer. As time expired, Rose took off his headband and whipped it across the court. It was Chicago's fourth loss in a row. Again, the Bulls were on the losing end at the free-throw line. The Clippers went to the line 25 times compared with just nine for Chicago. Brand, the No. 1 pick in the 1999 draft, got a warm ovation when he was introduced before the game. Expected to be the cornerstone in the post-Jordan rebuilding effort, the Bulls dumped him on draft day last year, shipping him to the Clippers for the rights to high schooler Tyson Chandler. Game notes
Bulls G Jamal Crawford, who missed the first 58 games after tearing a ligament in his left knee, played without his knee brace. ... Chicago rookie Tyson Chandler, who sat out his fourth game with a hyperextended left pinky, should return next week, but coach Bill Cartwright wasn't sure when. ... Both teams finished with 12 turnovers, but the Bulls gave up 13 points off theirs.
